1 Introduction

The aim of this homework to apply time series regression on a macroeconomic indicator. The last digit of my student ID is “2”, so my target variable is the consumer price index for alcoholic beverages and tobacco. After building the model, I will provide a forecast of CPI for alcoholic beverages and tobacco of April 2021, so the monthly data up to April 2021 will be used. Also, I will use other predictors to improve the forecast. All the data will be obtained from EVDS.

As independent predictors, I decided to use USD/TRY exchange rate because I believe it has a significant impact on almost all macroeconomic indicators of Turkey. Also, another statistics that I think might be relevant are the import statistics of unprocessed and processed materials of food and beverages. From the survey statistics of EVDS, I will use general economic situation, which I think may be related.

2 Analysis

2.1 Loading the data & preparation

Loading the required packages:

library(EVDS)
library(zoo)
library(lubridate)
library(dplyr)
library(ggplot2)
library(forecast)
library(GGally)
library(data.table)
Sys.setlocale("LC_TIME", "English")

I decided start date as 2013 because prior to 2013 most of the regressors that I want to use do not have the data. Also, I thought 8 years of data would be enough to come up with a good prediction.

data <- get_series(series = c("TP.FG.J02","TP.TG2.Y04","TP.TG2.Y11","TP.DK.USD.A.YTL","TP.ITHALATBEC.121","TP.ITHALATBEC.111"), start_date = "01-01-2013", end_date = "01-03-2021")
df <- data$items[,-8]
df1 <- df %>%
  mutate(Date=as.yearmon(Tarih, "%Y-%m"),
         cpi_alcohol_tobacco=as.numeric(TP_FG_J02),
         general_economic_situation=as.numeric(TP_TG2_Y04), 
         USD_TRY=as.numeric(TP_DK_USD_A_YTL), 
         import_processed_food_beverage=as.numeric(TP_ITHALATBEC_121), 
         import_unprocessed_food_beverage=as.numeric(TP_ITHALATBEC_111)) %>%
  select(Date:import_unprocessed_food_beverage)

2.2 Target variable

ggplot(df1, aes(x=Date,y=cpi_alcohol_tobacco))+
  geom_line()+
  theme_minimal()+
  labs(y="CPI for alcoholic beverages and tobacco", title = "Monthly CPI for Alcoholic Beverages and Tobacco")+
  scale_x_yearmon(n=10)+
  geom_smooth()

From my point of view, CPI for alcohol and tobacco mostly depends on tax increases, instead of raw material and processing costs. So before starting my analysis, I anticipated to see periodic increases, especially in the beginning of each year. I was not wrong, but also there are increases in other months, which I think is surprising.

We see a clear increasing trend, so trend component should be included in the model. Although we did not see an obvious seasonality, it is observed that there are subsequent sharp increases with similar periods in between. So it would be nicer if month columns are added and included in the model.

Also, I noticed that smoothed line has a slightly exponential trend. That is why I thought taking the logarithm of the target variable could be a great idea.

df1 <- df1 %>%
  mutate(log_target=log(cpi_alcohol_tobacco))

ggplot(df1, aes(x=Date,y=log_target))+
  geom_line()+
  theme_minimal()+
  labs(y="log(CPI) for alcoholic beverages and tobacco", title = "Monthly log(CPI) for Alcoholic Beverages and Tobacco")+
  scale_x_yearmon(n=10)+
  geom_smooth()

  mutate(lag1=lag(log_target,1),
         lag3=lag(log_target,3),
         lag6=lag(log_target,6),
         lag12=lag(log_target,12))

model3 <- lm(log_target~trend+as.factor(month)+lag1+lag3+lag6+lag12, df1)

2.7 Forecast

data <- get_series(series = c("TP.FG.J02","TP.TG2.Y04","TP.TG2.Y11","TP.DK.USD.A.YTL","TP.ITHALATBEC.121","TP.ITHALATBEC.111"), start_date = "01-04-2021", end_date = "01-04-2021")
df <- data$items[,-8]
df2 <- df %>%
  mutate(Date=as.yearmon(Tarih, "%Y-%m"),
         cpi_alcohol_tobacco=as.numeric(TP_FG_J02),
         general_economic_situation=as.numeric(TP_TG2_Y04), 
         USD_TRY=as.numeric(TP_DK_USD_A_YTL), 
         import_processed_food_beverage=as.numeric(TP_ITHALATBEC_121), 
         import_unprocessed_food_beverage=as.numeric(TP_ITHALATBEC_111)) %>%
  select(Date:import_unprocessed_food_beverage)

fc1 <-forecast(df1$import_processed_food_beverage)
fc2 <-forecast(df1$import_unprocessed_food_beverage)
df2 <- df2%>%
  mutate(
    log_target=NA,
    trend=100,
    month=4,
    lag1=6.779547,
    import_processed_food_beverage=fc1$mean[1],
    import_unprocessed_food_beverage=fc2$mean[1]
  )

exp(predict(model4, newdata = df2))
##        1 
## 899.7639

3 Conclusion

In this homework, the data of CPI for alcoholic beverages and tobacco is analyzed and an autoregressive time series regression is built. Even the simple models were sufficient to build a model with a quite high R-squared value. But in simpler models, residuals are autocorrelated. By adding independent variables and lagged target values, I managed to get rid of the autocorrelation of residuals and obtained a very high R-squared value. But even in that case there were outlier residuals, which I could not manage to eliminate.

My forecast for the 04-2021 is 899.7639. By the time I submit the homework, CPI for alcoholic beverages and tobacco value is already announced as 886.09, which proves my model overestimated the target variable.
